des. Emphasizing the importance of social networks, communication, and the symbolic and material exchanges that strengthen communities, social capital has been the subject of an expansive body of literature. Social Capital, Diversity, and the Welfare State represents a landmark consideration of the diverse meanings, causal foundations, and positive and negative consequences of social capital, with a particular focus on its role in mitigating or enhancing social inequalities. The chapters, written by economists, political scientists, and sociologists, address a range of empirical and theoretical issues. This book is cutting-edge addition to the field that offers fresh insights into the conceptualization, operation, sources, and consequences of social capital in Canadian society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCultural pluralismzCanada. 0aMulticulturalismzCanada. 0aSocial capital (Sociology)zCanada. 0aTrustxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aWelfare statezCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh1 aAbraham, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAizlewood, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanting, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernard, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurtis, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEisenberg, Avigail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelliwell, John F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKay, Fiona M., econtributor.4ctb4ht